    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>INTEL SEEKS ISRAELI AID</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By William A. Orme Jr.</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Orme, William A Jr</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Intel Corp is seeking Israeli state financial assistance for expansion of its $1.6 billion chip factory in Kiryat Gat; company executives tell Finance Min Avraham Shochat that proposed $3 billion project would generate up to 3,000 new jobs and $2 billion in annual exports; Intel's current Kiryat Gat factory is subsidized by much criticized $600 million package of grants and tax credits (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The giant computer chip company Intel is seeking Israeli state financial assistance for an expansion of its $1.6 billion chip factory in the town of Kiryat Gat. Company executives told Israel's finance minister, Avraham Shochat, that the proposed $3 billion project would generate up to 3,000 new jobs and $2 billion in annual exports. Intel's current Kiryat Gat factory, Israel's largest high-technology manufacturing plant, was subsidized by a much criticized $600 million package of grants and tax credits.</p>
        <p>William A. Orme Jr.</p>
      </block>
